{
  "answer": "**In *Traité de Législation*, Volume I, Chapter 18, Charles Comte defines the domains of morality and legislation (public authority/government) by distinguishing the forces that regulate human actions.**\n\nThe precise sentence is: \"Whenever men are led to execute certain actions, or to abstain from them by forces inherent in human nature, and without the intervention of governments, these forces are given the name of *moral laws*, or more simply of *morality*.\"[^1]\n\nComte immediately elaborates that \"to violate the laws of morality is to give oneself over to baneful actions that public authority does not repress: in this sense, it is very true to say that it is not enough for a thing not to have been forbidden by a government, for it to be licit.\"[^1]\n\nThis draws a clear boundary: **morality** governs actions via natural, inherent human forces (e.g., physical/moral pains or rewards from consequences) outside governmental reach; **legislation** applies public authority to repress or encourage other actions (e.g., crimes via penalties). He reinforces this in Chapter 21: actions \"outside the authority of governments... remain in the domain of morality.\"[^2]\n\nNo other sentence in Vol. I more precisely defines them as separate domains; earlier chapters (e.g., Ch. 2) note overlaps in study but not a functional separation.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/18-des-elements-de-puissance-dont-se-composent-les-lo/translation/#p-06a027).\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [paragraph](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/21-de-l-action-des-lois-de-la-morale-et-des-obstacles/translation/#p-4cf594).\n[^3]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, Chapter 2, [full chapter](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/02-de-la-methode-analytique-appliquee-a-l-etude-de-la/translation/).",
